  "id": "",
  "summary": "Heavily obfuscated source files across.ad/ directory require manual review",
  "details": "The package ships ~45 JavaScript files under a hidden `.ad/` directory (filenames like `x0.js` through `xz.js`, plus `from-generator.js`, `phone-validator.js`, `sms-providers.js`, `smtp-health-cache.js`, `web-command.js`) that are heavily obfuscated using hex-mangled identifier names (e.g. `_0x22511f`, `_0x5b1a89`). Obfuscation at this scale is unusual for an npm library and obstructs review of the actual runtime behavior. The filename hints (`sms-providers`, `smtp-health-cache`, `phone-validator`) suggest functionality related to SMS / SMTP / phone-number processing that may be unwanted by a typical installer. Concrete installer-harm behavior (network destinations, credential reads, lifecycle-script execution paths) was not conclusively traced from this package's contents, so a definitive attack classification cannot be made on the available evidence. Routing to human review so a reviewer can de-obfuscate the `.ad/` files, confirm whether they are imported at install/import time, and determine whether the runtime behavior matches the package's advertised purpose.",
